subsection.p:
For integrals, the rule is
\boxed{ \int_S \alpha=\int_D \mathbf r^*\alpha, }
when \alpha is a form of degree 2 on the surface.

The coefficients are exactly the components of the curl:
\boxed{ \nabla\times\mathbf F = (R_y-Q_z,\;P_z-R_x,\;Q_x-P_y). }
So
\boxed{ d\omega=\Phi_{\nabla\times\mathbf F}, }
where
\Phi_{\nabla\times\mathbf F}
is the flux 2-form of the vector field \nabla\times\mathbf F.

statement.p:
Equivalently, for the vector field
\mathbf F=(P,Q,R),
\boxed{ \oint_{\partial S}\mathbf F\cdot d\mathbf r = \iint_S(\nabla\times\mathbf F)\cdot \widehat{\mathbf n}\,dS. }

subsection.p:
Compute the boundary integral. Parametrize C by x=a\cos t,\qquad y=a\sin t,\qquad z=0, \qquad 0\le t\le2\pi. Then dx=-a\sin t\,dt, \qquad dy=a\cos t\,dt. So
\omega \amp= -\frac{a\sin t}{2}(-a\sin t\,dt) + \frac{a\cos t}{2}(a\cos t\,dt)\\ \amp= \frac{a^2}{2}(\sin^2 t+\cos^2 t)\,dt\\ \amp= \frac{a^2}{2}\,dt.
Thus \boxed{ \int_C\omega=\pi a^2. }

On the unit circle in the plane z=0, x=\cos t,\qquad y=\sin t, so dx=-\sin t\,dt,\qquad dy=\cos t\,dt. Then
\alpha \amp= -\sin t(-\sin t\,dt)+\cos t(\cos t\,dt)\\ \amp= dt.
Therefore \boxed{ \int_C\alpha=2\pi. }
